snippet.textDisplay:
Lesson here: leave books around for kids to explore. dont just shove them at them.


Been like that with me too...didnt read HarryPotter until I was 16 bc I didnt like being pressured into it. I read way more when I get to decide what I read. Which is why I got a list of books that my entire family apparently ignores and instead opts to gift me books of the one author of which I liked a singular series of or other stuff Im not gonna touch in the next years...


Also yes schools make reading exhausting and boring and tbf their book choices are stale and tiring. My school didnt even go along with the more classic books like Kafka or sth vaguely cool..we just got some books about teenage alcoholism, teenage delinquency and other shit that 14y old me didnt enjoy bc they never had a good ending?? Like talk about motivating when the message is "yall going to jail". So the only good stuff we were left with were the real classics like Goethe or Schiller which I took a liking in bc at least there I knew not to expect sth uplifting....also I got to do the entire group works there on my own since no one else read it....but it also meant I got to execute the protag in our acted out trial at the end of it

snippet.textDisplay:
I can relate to school sucking the joy out of reading. I LOVE to read, but I HATED having to read assigned books and analyze them and all that crap. With the exception of Fahrenheit 451, which I found that I actually really liked, all assigned books that I had to read were boring as hell and I don't remember anything else about them.

I have kids now & I really want them to love reading too, but I've come to realize that my oldest will avoid any book I have the nerve to suggest (not order) he read, no matter what it is. He's practically a cat when it comes to reading -- I have to ignore him & hope he chooses to pick up a book. (Fortunately he'll choose books from his school library.)
snippet.textOriginal:

I have kids now & I really want them to love reading too, but I've come to realize that my oldest will avoid any book I have the nerve to suggest (not order) he read, no matter what it is.
